      <h2>Types Of Herniations</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Posterolateral Disc Hernation</summary>
        <p>
          Protrusion is usually posterolateral into vertebral canal. Protruded
          disc usually compresses next lower nerve as the nerve crosses the
          level of disc in its path to its foramen. (Example: protrusion of L5
          usually affects S1).
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Cental (Posterior) Hernation</summary>
        <p>
          It is less frequent. A protruded disc above 2nd vertebra may compress
          the spinal cord itself or may lead to
          <strong>Cauda Equina Syndrome.</strong>
        </p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Lateral Disc Hernation</summary>
        <p>
          Nerve root compression happens above the level of herniation. L4 nerve
          root is most often involved.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
